#  Day 36 – The Information Lifecycle: Governing Patient Data from Creation to Disposal | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## Data Does Not Stand Still

One thing that has shifted in my thinking as this project has developed is how I picture the data in OpenMRS. Early on I was thinking about it primarily as a static asset — data sitting in a database that needs to be protected. The information lifecycle work today challenged that picture in a useful way.

Patient records in OpenMRS are not static. They are created, updated, transmitted, stored, archived, and eventually disposed of. At each stage of that journey, the data faces different risks, requires different controls, and involves different people and systems. A security program that focuses only on the storage phase — protecting the database — will miss risks at creation, transmission, archival, and disposal.

NIST SP 800-37 and the broader NIST information security framework treat the information lifecycle as a foundational concept precisely because the appropriate controls depend on what is happening to the data at a given point in its lifecycle. Today I worked through each phase of the lifecycle for OpenMRS patient records at MyClinic, mapping the specific risks and required controls at each stage.

---

## What I Worked On Today

The information lifecycle framework I used has five phases: Creation and Collection, Active Use and Maintenance, Storage and Retention, Archival, and Disposal. For each phase I worked through what happens to OpenMRS data at that stage, what the specific risks are, what controls are required, and what a failure at that stage would look like in practice.

The exercise connected directly to the information types documented on Day 35 — particularly the clinical health records and patient identity information that represent the highest sensitivity data in the system — and to the control families in NIST SP 800-53 that address information lifecycle management: MP (Media Protection), AU (Audit and Accountability), AC (Access Control), and SI (System and Information Integrity).

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The thing that clicked most clearly today is that data disposal is the phase most commonly handled poorly — and the consequences of poor disposal are just as serious as the consequences of a breach during active use.

Organizations invest heavily in protecting data while it is being actively used. But when data reaches the end of its lifecycle — when a record is deleted, when a server is decommissioned, when backup tapes are retired, when a cloud storage bucket is emptied — the same data that was carefully protected suddenly receives much less attention. The assumption is that deleted data is gone. But deletion without proper sanitization is often not permanent, and backup data that should be purged according to a retention policy often persists far beyond its intended lifecycle because nobody is actively managing it.

The 2013 Advocate Medical Group breach — which I covered briefly on Day 12 — involved stolen unencrypted laptops. Those laptops contained patient data that was resident on the device even though the organization's understanding was that patient data was not stored locally. The data was there — in temporary files, cached records, browser history — because nobody had managed the endpoint data lifecycle. The disposal and endpoint management phases had been overlooked.

That case reframed disposal for me from a compliance formality into a genuine security risk that deserves the same attention as access control and encryption.

