## What I Am Still Thinking About

The interaction between backup retention and patient record disposal is a practical challenge I want to think through more carefully.

The scenario is this: a patient record becomes eligible for disposal after the legally required retention period. The records team initiates disposal — the record is deleted from the active OpenMRS database and flagged for purge. But the S3 backup bucket contains daily snapshots going back 90 days (or whatever the backup retention period is). Those snapshots contain the patient record that was just deleted from the active system.

Options include: waiting for the backup copies to age out of the retention window before considering disposal complete (meaning effective disposal takes 90 days after the active record deletion); actively purging specific patient records from backup copies (technically complex and potentially disruptive to the backup integrity); or documenting that backup copies are subject to equivalent security controls and will be purged as the backup retention window advances.

I think the third approach is the most practical for a small clinic environment, but it needs to be documented explicitly in the disposal policy so that it is a deliberate decision rather than an oversight. I want to develop that documentation as part of the System Security Plan work.

